{"parse":{"title":"Topit","pageid":8816881,"revid":785881678,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>A <b>Topit</b> is a utility device used by <a href=\"/wiki/Magician_(illusion)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Magician (illusion)\">magicians</a> to dispose of objects secretly.  It plays a similar role in the magician's toolkit to pulls, holdouts, <a href=\"/wiki/Servantes_(magic)\" title=\"Servantes (magic)\">servantes</a>, and techniques such as <a href=\"/wiki/Sleeving\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Sleeving\">sleeving</a> or <a href=\"/wiki/Lapping_(magic)\" title=\"Lapping (magic)\">lapping</a>.    While the original Topit booklet by Patrick Page was put out by Lewis Davenport Ltd. in <a href=\"/wiki/London\" title=\"London\">London</a> decades ago, it was <a href=\"/wiki/Michael_Ammar\" title=\"Michael Ammar\">Michael Ammar</a> who popularized the Topit with his refinement of Topit technique and inspired a number of well-known close-up magicians to adopt it.\n<sup id=\"cite_ref-wilmarth_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-wilmarth-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Topits were employed by <a href=\"/wiki/Pickpocket\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Pickpocket\">pickpockets</a> and thieves during the 19th century. This primitive form of the topit was called the \"Poacher's Pouch\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-fitch_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-fitch-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\nThe art of Topit has developed, like some other forms of magic, in <a href=\"/wiki/Symbiotic_relationship\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Symbiotic relationship\">symbiotic relationship</a> between magicians and <a href=\"/wiki/Confidence_trick\" title=\"Confidence trick\">grifters</a>, both considered <a href=\"/wiki/Sleight_of_hand\" title=\"Sleight of hand\">sleight of hand</a> artists.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Topit&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-wilmarth-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-wilmarth_1-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Wilmarth, Phil (October 2003). \"Ramon's Topit Pattern (review)\". <i>The Linking Ring</i>. p.&#160;124.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Linking+Ring&amp;rft.atitle=Ramon%27s+Topit+Pattern+%28review%29&amp;rft.pages=124&amp;rft.date=2003-10&amp;rft.aulast=Wilmarth&amp;rft.aufirst=Phil&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ATopit\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-fitch-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-fitch_2-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Bob, Fitch (March 1999). \"A Topic On The Topit\". <i>The Linking Ring</i>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Linking+Ring&amp;rft.atitle=A+Topic+On+The+Topit&amp;rft.date=1999-03&amp;rft.aulast=Bob&amp;rft.aufirst=Fitch&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ATopit\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div>\n<div role=\"navigation\" class=\"navbox\" aria-labelledby=\"Magic_and_illusion\" style=\"padding:3px\"><table class=\"nowraplinks collapsible autocollapse navbox-inner\" style=\"border-spacing:0;background:transparent;color:inherit\"><tbody><tr><th scope=\"col\" class=\"navbox-title\" colspan=\"3\"><div class=\"plainlinks hlist navbar mini\"><ul><li class=\"nv-view\"><a href=\"/wiki/Template:Magic_and_illusion\" title=\"Template:Magic and il